Another 540,000 people were told to leave Georgia, where the authorities have opened hundreds of shelters for those who have decided not to leave.Forecasters have predicted a storm surge of 6 to 12 feet (1.8 - 3.6 meters) above ground level along Florida's southwest coast and in the Flordia Keys, the storm now expected to track towards the west coast of the state, away from the Miami metropolitan area, which is home to some 6 million people.Irma had weakened to a Category 4 storm with winds of 155 mph (250 kph) on Friday but forecasters said it could crank back up to Category 5 when it hits land near Key West, as expected on Sunday morning, local time. Irma has killed at least 20 people in the Caribbean and dozens more injured across several island nations.Irma is the most powerful hurricane ever recorded in the open Atlantic. Irma is expected to be the second major hurricane to make landfall in the US in less than two weeks after Hurricane Harvey struck Texas last week, killing more than 60 people and displacing roughly 1 million others.Disney World parks will close early Saturday and remain shuttered through Monday, as will Universal Orlando and Sea World.CoreLogic, a consultant to insurers, estimated that almost 8.5 million Florida homes or commercial properties were at extreme, very high or high risk of wind damage from Irma.This means "a less costly, a less deadly storm," University of Miami researcher Brian McNoldy told the Associated Press."This is a storm that will kill you if you don't get out of the way," National Hurricane Center meteorologist Dennis Feltgen said. "Everybody's going to feel this one." Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2jYwIBahamas lucky escapeThe Bahamas had a close call but ultimately escaped the worst of Irma's destructive wrath, with no casualties or major infrastructure damages reported.The storm passed through the southeast islands including Mayagua, Inagua, Crooked Island Acklins, Long Cay and Ragged Islands, on Thursday and Friday.More on the wayTwo other major storms have developed in the Caribbean, namely Hurricane Jose and Hurricane Katia. Jose was east of the Lesser Antilles with maximum winds of 120 miles per hour (195 kilometers per hour) as a hurricane watch was in effect for Antigua and Barbuda.Jose has followed the same path as Hurricane Irma and was upgraded to a Category 4 on Friday by the US National Hurricane Center. Katia has remained relatively static, hovering off the coast of Mexico.Katia made landfall in Mexico on Friday evening, the US National Hurricane Center said. The category 1 storm hit north of Tecolutla, the agency said, in the state of Veracruz on Mexico's Gulf Coast. Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2jTtYjbh/sms (AP, AFP)